":"FitzWilliam","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (of Norman origin): from Anglo-Norman French <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   William  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth FitzWilliam was born about 1187, in Hurworth-on-Tees, Durham, England, United Kingdom, her father, William FitzWilliam , of Hurworth, was 34 and her mother, Mrs. William FitzWilliam of Hurworth, was 30. She married William Bardulf about 1200, in Hurworth-on-Tees, Durham, England, United Kingdom. She died in 1256, in her hometown, at the age of 70."},"et":{"abt 1187–1256":"umbes 1187–1256","1181–1235":"1181–1235","1187–1256":"1187–1256","1186–1219":"1186–1219","1150–1206":"1150–1206","1211–Male":"1211–Surnud","1216–1257":"1216–1257","1155–1200":"1155–1200","1159–Female":"1159–Surnud","by 1206":"1206","1187":"1187","1186":"1186","abt 1187":"umbes 1187","1150":"1150","1181":"1181","1206":"1206","1216":"1216","1159":"1159","1257":"1257","1235":"1235","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1256":"1256","1200":"1200","1211":"1211","about 1216":"umbes 1216","1155":"1155","about 1211":"umbes 1211","by 1200":"1200","1219":"1219","of Hurworth, Durham, and Hephale, Northumberland, England":"Hurworth-on-Tees, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hurworth, Durham, England":"Hurworth-on-Tees, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hepple, Northumberland, England":"Hepple, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"abt 1187–1256":"noin 1187–1256","1181–1235":"1181–1235","1187–1256":"1187–1256","1186–1219":"1186–1219","1150–1206":"1150–1206","1211–Male":"1211–Kuollut","1216–1257":"1216–1257","1155–1200":"1155–1200","1159–Female":"1159–Kuollut","by 1206":"1206","1187":"1187","1186":"1186","abt 1187":"noin 1187","1150":"1150","1181":"1181","1206":"1206","1216":"1216","1159":"1159","1257":"1257","1235":"1235","Abt 1200":"noin 1200","1256":"1256","1200":"1200","1211":"1211","about 1216":"noin 1216","1155":"1155","about 1211":"noin 1211","by 1200":"1200","1219":"1219","of Hurworth, Durham, and Hephale, Northumberland, England":"Hurworth-on-Tees, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hurworth, Durham, England":"Hurwor